#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:3
msgid "Using F2PY bindings in Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:5
msgid ""
"In this page, you can find a full description and a few examples of common "
"usage patterns for F2PY with Python and different argument types. For more "
"examples and use cases, see :ref:`f2py-examples`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:10
msgid "Fortran type objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:12
msgid ""
"All wrappers for Fortran/C routines, common blocks, or Fortran 90 module "
"data generated by F2PY are exposed to Python as ``fortran`` type objects. "
"Routine wrappers are callable ``fortran`` type objects while wrappers to "
"Fortran data have attributes referring to data objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:17
msgid ""
"All ``fortran`` type objects have an attribute ``_cpointer`` that contains "
"a :c:type:`PyCapsule` referring to the C pointer of the corresponding "
"Fortran/C function or variable at the C level. Such ``PyCapsule`` objects "
"can be used as callback arguments for F2PY generated functions to bypass the "
"Python C/API layer for calling Python functions from Fortran or C. This can "
"be useful when the computational aspects of such functions are implemented "
"in C or Fortran and wrapped with F2PY (or any other tool capable of "
"providing the ``PyCapsule`` containing a function)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:26
msgid "Consider a Fortran 77 file ```ftype.f``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:28
msgid ""
"C FILE: FTYPE.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO(N)\n"
"      INTEGER N\n"
"Cf2py integer optional,intent(in) :: n = 13\n"
"      REAL A,X\n"
"      COMMON /DATA/ A,X(3)\n"
"C     PRINT*, \"IN FOO: N=\",N,\" A=\",A,\" X=[\",X(1),X(2),X(3),\"]\"\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF FTYPE.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:31
msgid "and a wrapper built using ``f2py -c ftype.f -m ftype``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:33
msgid ""
"In Python, you can observe the types of ``foo`` and ``data``, and how to "
"access individual objects of the wrapped Fortran code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:36
msgid ""
">>> import ftype\n"
">>> print(ftype.__doc__)\n"
"This module 'ftype' is auto-generated with f2py (version:2).\n"
"Functions:\n"
"  foo(n=13)\n"
"COMMON blocks:\n"
"  /data/ a,x(3)\n"
".\n"
">>> type(ftype.foo), type(ftype.data)\n"
"(<class 'fortran'>, <class 'fortran'>)\n"
">>> ftype.foo()\n"
" IN FOO: N= 13 A=  0. X=[  0.  0.  0.]\n"
">>> ftype.data.a = 3\n"
">>> ftype.data.x = [1,2,3]\n"
">>> ftype.foo()\n"
" IN FOO: N= 13 A=  3. X=[  1.  2.  3.]\n"
">>> ftype.data.x[1] = 45  \n"
">>> ftype.foo(24)\n"
" IN FOO: N= 24 A=  3. X=[  1.  45.  3.]\n"
">>> ftype.data.x\n"
"array([  1.,  45.,   3.], dtype=float32)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:41
msgid "Scalar arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:43
msgid ""
"In general, a scalar argument for a F2PY generated wrapper function can be "
"an ordinary Python scalar (integer, float, complex number) as well as an "
"arbitrary sequence object (list, tuple, array, string) of scalars. In the "
"latter case, the first element of the sequence object is passed to the "
"Fortran routine as a scalar argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:51
msgid ""
"When type-casting is required and there is possible loss of information via "
"narrowing e.g. when type-casting float to integer or complex to float, F2PY "
"*does not* raise an exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:55
msgid ""
"For complex to real type-casting only the real part of a complex number is "
"used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:58
msgid ""
"``intent(inout)`` scalar arguments are assumed to be array objects in order "
"to have *in situ* changes be effective. It is recommended to use arrays with "
"proper type but also other types work. :ref:`Read more about the intent "
"attribute <f2py-attributes>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:63 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:95
#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:140 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:159
#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:314
msgid "Consider the following Fortran 77 code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:65
msgid ""
"C FILE: SCALAR.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,B)\n"
"      REAL*8 A, B\n"
"Cf2py intent(in) a\n"
"Cf2py intent(inout) b\n"
"      PRINT*, \"    A=\",A,\" B=\",B\n"
"      PRINT*, \"INCREMENT A AND B\"\n"
"      A = A + 1D0\n"
"      B = B + 1D0\n"
"      PRINT*, \"NEW A=\",A,\" B=\",B\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF FILE SCALAR.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:68
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m scalar scalar.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:70 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:147
#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:166 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:219
#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:242 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:321
#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:340 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:358
msgid "In Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:72
msgid ""
">>> import scalar\n"
">>> print(scalar.foo.__doc__)\n"
"foo(a,b)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input float\n"
"b : in/output rank-0 array(float,'d')\n"
" \n"
">>> scalar.foo(2, 3)   \n"
"     A=  2. B=  3.\n"
" INCREMENT A AND B\n"
" NEW A=  3. B=  4.\n"
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> a = numpy.array(2)   # these are integer rank-0 arrays\n"
">>> b = numpy.array(3)\n"
">>> scalar.foo(a, b)\n"
"     A=  2. B=  3.\n"
" INCREMENT A AND B\n"
" NEW A=  3. B=  4.\n"
">>> print(a, b)          # note that only b is changed in situ\n"
"2 4\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:77
msgid "String arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:79
msgid ""
"F2PY generated wrapper functions accept almost any Python object as a string "
"argument, since ``str`` is applied for non-string objects. Exceptions are "
"NumPy arrays that must have type code ``'S1'`` or ``'b'`` (corresponding to "
"the outdated ``'c'`` or ``'1'`` typecodes, respectively) when used as string "
"arguments. See :ref:`arrays.scalars` for more information on these typecodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:85
msgid ""
"A string can have an arbitrary length when used as a string argument for an "
"F2PY generated wrapper function. If the length is greater than expected, the "
"string is truncated silently. If the length is smaller than expected, "
"additional memory is allocated and filled with ``\\0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:92
msgid ""
"Because Python strings are immutable, an ``intent(inout)`` argument expects "
"an array version of a string in order to have *in situ* changes be effective."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:97
msgid ""
"C FILE: STRING.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,B,C,D)\n"
"      CHARACTER*5 A, B\n"
"      CHARACTER*(*) C,D\n"
"Cf2py intent(in) a,c\n"
"Cf2py intent(inout) b,d\n"
"      PRINT*, \"A=\",A\n"
"      PRINT*, \"B=\",B\n"
"      PRINT*, \"C=\",C\n"
"      PRINT*, \"D=\",D\n"
"      PRINT*, \"CHANGE A,B,C,D\"\n"
"      A(1:1) = 'A'\n"
"      B(1:1) = 'B'\n"
"      C(1:1) = 'C'\n"
"      D(1:1) = 'D'\n"
"      PRINT*, \"A=\",A\n"
"      PRINT*, \"B=\",B\n"
"      PRINT*, \"C=\",C\n"
"      PRINT*, \"D=\",D\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF FILE STRING.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:100
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m mystring string.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:102
msgid "Python session:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:104
msgid ""
">>> import mystring\n"
">>> print(mystring.foo.__doc__)\n"
"foo(a,b,c,d)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input string(len=5)\n"
"b : in/output rank-0 array(string(len=5),'c')\n"
"c : input string(len=-1)\n"
"d : in/output rank-0 array(string(len=-1),'c')\n"
"\n"
">>> from numpy import array\n"
">>> a = array(b'123\\0\\0')\n"
">>> b = array(b'123\\0\\0')\n"
">>> c = array(b'123')\n"
">>> d = array(b'123')\n"
">>> mystring.foo(a, b, c, d)\n"
" A=123\n"
" B=123\n"
" C=123\n"
" D=123\n"
" CHANGE A,B,C,D\n"
" A=A23\n"
" B=B23\n"
" C=C23\n"
" D=D23\n"
">>> a[()], b[()], c[()], d[()]\n"
"(b'123', b'B23', b'123', b'D2')\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:109
msgid "Array arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:111
msgid ""
"In general, array arguments for F2PY generated wrapper functions accept "
"arbitrary sequences that can be transformed to NumPy array objects. There "
"are two notable exceptions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:115
msgid ""
"``intent(inout)`` array arguments must always be :term:`proper-contiguous "
"<contiguous>` and have a compatible ``dtype``, otherwise an exception is "
"raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:118
msgid ""
"``intent(inplace)`` array arguments must be arrays. If these have "
"incompatible order or size, a converted copy is passed in, which is copied "
"back into the original array on exit (see the ``intent(inplace)`` :ref:"
"`attribute <f2py-attributes>` for more information)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:123
msgid ""
"In general, if a NumPy array is :term:`proper-contiguous <contiguous>` and "
"has a proper type then it is directly passed to the wrapped Fortran/C "
"function. Otherwise, an element-wise copy of the input array is made and the "
"copy, being proper-contiguous and with proper type, is used as the array "
"argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:128
msgid ""
"Usually there is no need to worry about how the arrays are stored in memory "
"and whether the wrapped functions, being either Fortran or C functions, "
"assume one or another storage order. F2PY automatically ensures that wrapped "
"functions get arguments with the proper storage order; the underlying "
"algorithm is designed to make copies of arrays only when absolutely "
"necessary. However, when dealing with very large multidimensional input "
"arrays with sizes close to the size of the physical memory in your computer, "
"then care must be taken to ensure the usage of proper-contiguous and proper "
"type arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:137
msgid ""
"To transform input arrays to column major storage order before passing them "
"to Fortran routines, use the function `numpy.asfortranarray`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:142
msgid ""
"C FILE: ARRAY.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,N,M)\n"
"C\n"
"C     INCREMENT THE FIRST ROW AND DECREMENT THE FIRST COLUMN OF A\n"
"C\n"
"      INTEGER N,M,I,J\n"
"      REAL*8 A(N,M)\n"
"Cf2py intent(in,out,copy) a\n"
"Cf2py integer intent(hide),depend(a) :: n=shape(a,0), m=shape(a,1)\n"
"      DO J=1,M\n"
"         A(1,J) = A(1,J) + 1D0\n"
"      ENDDO\n"
"      DO I=1,N\n"
"         A(I,1) = A(I,1) - 1D0\n"
"      ENDDO\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF FILE ARRAY.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:145
msgid ""
"and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m arr array.f -DF2PY_REPORT_ON_ARRAY_COPY=1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:149
msgid ""
">>> import arr\n"
">>> from numpy import asfortranarray\n"
">>> print(arr.foo.__doc__)\n"
"a = foo(a,[overwrite_a])\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input rank-2 array('d') with bounds (n,m)\n"
"\n"
"Other Parameters\n"
"----------------\n"
"overwrite_a : input int, optional\n"
"    Default: 0\n"
"\n"
"Returns\n"
"-------\n"
"a : rank-2 array('d') with bounds (n,m)\n"
"\n"
">>> a = arr.foo([[1, 2, 3],\n"
"...              [4, 5, 6]])\n"
"created an array from object\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[[ 1.  3.  4.]\n"
" [ 3.  5.  6.]]\n"
">>> a.flags.c_contiguous\n"
"False\n"
">>> a.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
"# even if a is proper-contiguous and has proper type,\n"
"# a copy is made forced by intent(copy) attribute\n"
"# to preserve its original contents\n"
">>> b = arr.foo(a)\n"
"copied an array: size=6, elsize=8\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[[ 1.  3.  4.]\n"
" [ 3.  5.  6.]]\n"
">>> print(b)\n"
"[[ 1.  4.  5.]\n"
" [ 2.  5.  6.]]\n"
">>> b = arr.foo(a, overwrite_a = 1) # a is passed directly to Fortran\n"
"...                                 # routine and its contents is discarded\n"
"... \n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[[ 1.  4.  5.]\n"
" [ 2.  5.  6.]]\n"
">>> print(b)\n"
"[[ 1.  4.  5.]\n"
" [ 2.  5.  6.]]\n"
">>> a is b                          # a and b are actually the same objects\n"
"True\n"
">>> print(arr.foo([1, 2, 3]))       # different rank arrays are allowed\n"
"created an array from object\n"
"[ 1.  1.  2.]\n"
">>> print(arr.foo([[[1], [2], [3]]]))\n"
"created an array from object\n"
"[[[ 1.]\n"
"  [ 1.]\n"
"  [ 2.]]]\n"
">>>\n"
">>> # Creating arrays with column major data storage order:\n"
" ...\n"
">>> s = asfortranarray([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]])\n"
">>> s.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
">>> print(s)\n"
"[[1 2 3]\n"
" [4 5 6]]\n"
">>> print(arr.foo(s))\n"
">>> s2 = asfortranarray(s)\n"
">>> s2 is s    # an array with column major storage order \n"
"               # is returned immediately\n"
"True\n"
">>> # Note that arr.foo returns a column major data storage order array:\n"
" ...\n"
">>> s3 = ascontiguousarray(s)\n"
">>> s3.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"False\n"
">>> s3.flags.c_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
">>> s3 = arr.foo(s3)\n"
"copied an array: size=6, elsize=8\n"
">>> s3.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
">>> s3.flags.c_contiguous\n"
"False\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:155
msgid "Call-back arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:157
msgid "F2PY supports calling Python functions from Fortran or C codes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:161
msgid ""
"C FILE: CALLBACK.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO(FUN,R)\n"
"      EXTERNAL FUN\n"
"      INTEGER I\n"
"      REAL*8 R, FUN\n"
"Cf2py intent(out) r\n"
"      R = 0D0\n"
"      DO I=-5,5\n"
"         R = R + FUN(I)\n"
"      ENDDO\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF FILE CALLBACK.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:164
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m callback callback.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:168
msgid ""
">>> import callback\n"
">>> print(callback.foo.__doc__)\n"
"r = foo(fun,[fun_extra_args])\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"fun : call-back function\n"
"\n"
"Other Parameters\n"
"----------------\n"
"fun_extra_args : input tuple, optional\n"
"    Default: ()\n"
"\n"
"Returns\n"
"-------\n"
"r : float\n"
"\n"
"Notes\n"
"-----\n"
"Call-back functions::\n"
"\n"
"  def fun(i): return r\n"
"  Required arguments:\n"
"    i : input int\n"
"  Return objects:\n"
"    r : float\n"
"\n"
">>> def f(i): return i*i\n"
"... \n"
">>> print(callback.foo(f))\n"
"110.0\n"
">>> print(callback.foo(lambda i:1))\n"
"11.0\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:171
msgid ""
"In the above example F2PY was able to guess accurately the signature of the "
"call-back function. However, sometimes F2PY cannot establish the appropriate "
"signature; in these cases the signature of the call-back function must be "
"explicitly defined in the signature file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:176
msgid ""
"To facilitate this, signature files may contain special modules (the names "
"of these modules contain the special ``__user__`` sub-string) that define "
"the various signatures for call-back functions.  Callback arguments in "
"routine signatures have the ``external`` attribute (see also the "
"``intent(callback)`` :ref:`attribute <f2py-attributes>`). To relate a "
"callback argument with its signature in a ``__user__`` module block, a "
"``use`` statement can be utilized as illustrated below. The same signature "
"for a callback argument can be referred to in different routine signatures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:185
msgid ""
"We use the same Fortran 77 code as in the previous example but now we will "
"pretend that F2PY was not able to guess the signatures of call-back "
"arguments correctly. First, we create an initial signature file ``callback2."
"pyf`` using F2PY::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:190
msgid "f2py -m callback2 -h callback2.pyf callback.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:192
msgid "Then modify it as follows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:1
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"python module __user__routines \n"
"    interface\n"
"        function fun(i) result (r)\n"
"            integer :: i\n"
"            real*8 :: r\n"
"        end function fun\n"
"    end interface\n"
"end python module __user__routines\n"
"\n"
"python module callback2\n"
"    interface\n"
"        subroutine foo(f,r)\n"
"            use __user__routines, f=>fun\n"
"            external f\n"
"            real*8 intent(out) :: r\n"
"        end subroutine foo\n"
"    end interface \n"
"end python module callback2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:197
msgid ""
"Finally, we build the extension module using ``f2py -c callback2.pyf "
"callback.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:200
msgid ""
"An example Python session for this snippet would be identical to the "
"previous example except that the argument names would differ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:203
msgid ""
"Sometimes a Fortran package may require that users provide routines that the "
"package will use. F2PY can construct an interface to such routines so that "
"Python functions can be called from Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:207
msgid ""
"Consider the following Fortran 77 subroutine that takes an array as its "
"input and applies a function ``func`` to its elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:210
msgid ""
"      subroutine calculate(x,n)\n"
"cf2py intent(callback) func\n"
"      external func\n"
"c     The following lines define the signature of func for F2PY:\n"
"cf2py real*8 y\n"
"cf2py y = func(y)\n"
"c\n"
"cf2py intent(in,out,copy) x\n"
"      integer n,i\n"
"      real*8 x(n), func\n"
"      do i=1,n\n"
"         x(i) = func(x(i))\n"
"      end do\n"
"      end\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:213
msgid ""
"The Fortran code expects that the function ``func`` has been defined "
"externally. In order to use a Python function for ``func``, it must have an "
"attribute ``intent(callback)`` and it must be specified before the "
"``external`` statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:217
msgid "Finally, build an extension module using ``f2py -c -m foo calculate.f``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:221
msgid ""
">>> import foo\n"
">>> foo.calculate(range(5), lambda x: x*x)\n"
"array([  0.,   1.,   4.,   9.,  16.])\n"
">>> import math\n"
">>> foo.calculate(range(5), math.exp)\n"
"array([  1.        ,   2.71828183,   7.3890561,  20.08553692,  "
"54.59815003])\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:224
msgid ""
"The function is included as an argument to the python function call to the "
"Fortran subroutine even though it was *not* in the Fortran subroutine "
"argument list. The \"external\" keyword refers to the C function generated "
"by f2py, not the Python function itself. The python function is essentially "
"being supplied to the C function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:230
msgid ""
"The callback function may also be explicitly set in the module. Then it is "
"not necessary to pass the function in the argument list to the Fortran "
"function. This may be desired if the Fortran function calling the Python "
"callback function is itself called by another Fortran function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:235
msgid "Consider the following Fortran 77 subroutine:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:237
msgid ""
"      subroutine f1()\n"
"         print *, \"in f1, calling f2 twice..\"\n"
"         call f2()\n"
"         call f2()\n"
"         return\n"
"      end\n"
"      \n"
"      subroutine f2()\n"
"cf2py    intent(callback, hide) fpy\n"
"         external fpy\n"
"         print *, \"in f2, calling f2py..\"\n"
"         call fpy()\n"
"         return\n"
"      end\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:240
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m pfromf extcallback.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:244
msgid ""
">>> import pfromf\n"
">>> pfromf.f2()\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"pfromf.error: Callback fpy not defined (as an argument or module pfromf "
"attribute).\n"
"\n"
">>> def f(): print(\"python f\")\n"
"... \n"
">>> pfromf.fpy = f\n"
">>> pfromf.f2()\n"
" in f2, calling f2py..\n"
"python f\n"
">>> pfromf.f1()\n"
" in f1, calling f2 twice..\n"
" in f2, calling f2py..\n"
"python f\n"
" in f2, calling f2py..\n"
"python f\n"
">>> "
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:249
msgid ""
"When using modified Fortran code via ``callstatement`` or other directives, "
"the wrapped Python function must be called as a callback, otherwise only the "
"bare Fortran routine will be used. For more details, see https://github.com/"
"numpy/numpy/issues/26681#issuecomment-2466460943"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:255
msgid "Resolving arguments to call-back functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:257
msgid ""
"F2PY generated interfaces are very flexible with respect to call-back "
"arguments.  For each call-back argument an additional optional argument "
"``<name>_extra_args`` is introduced by F2PY. This argument can be used to "
"pass extra arguments to user provided call-back functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:261
msgid ""
"If a F2PY generated wrapper function expects the following call-back "
"argument::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:263
msgid ""
"def fun(a_1,...,a_n):\n"
"   ...\n"
"   return x_1,...,x_k"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:267
msgid "but the following Python function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:271
msgid ""
"def gun(b_1,...,b_m):\n"
"   ...\n"
"   return y_1,...,y_l"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:275
msgid "is provided by a user, and in addition,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:279
msgid "fun_extra_args = (e_1,...,e_p)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:281
msgid ""
"is used, then the following rules are applied when a Fortran or C function "
"evaluates the call-back argument ``gun``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:284
msgid ""
"If ``p == 0`` then ``gun(a_1, ..., a_q)`` is called, here ``q = min(m, n)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:286
msgid "If ``n + p <= m`` then ``gun(a_1, ..., a_n, e_1, ..., e_p)`` is called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:287
msgid ""
"If ``p <= m < n + p`` then ``gun(a_1, ..., a_q, e_1, ..., e_p)`` is called, "
"and here ``q=m-p``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:289
msgid "If ``p > m`` then ``gun(e_1, ..., e_m)`` is called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:290
msgid ""
"If ``n + p`` is less than the number of required arguments to ``gun`` then "
"an exception is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:293
msgid ""
"If the function ``gun`` may return any number of objects as a tuple; then "
"the following rules are applied:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:296
msgid "If ``k < l``, then ``y_{k + 1}, ..., y_l`` are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:297
msgid "If ``k > l``, then only ``x_1, ..., x_l`` are set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:301
msgid "Common blocks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:303
msgid ""
"F2PY generates wrappers to ``common`` blocks defined in a routine signature "
"block. Common blocks are visible to all Fortran codes linked to the current "
"extension module, but not to other extension modules (this restriction is "
"due to the way Python imports shared libraries). In Python, the F2PY "
"wrappers to ``common`` blocks are ``fortran`` type objects that have "
"(dynamic) attributes related to the data members of the common blocks. When "
"accessed, these attributes return as NumPy array objects (multidimensional "
"arrays are Fortran-contiguous) which directly link to data members in common "
"blocks. Data members can be changed by direct assignment or by in-place "
"changes to the corresponding array objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:316
msgid ""
"C FILE: COMMON.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FOO\n"
"      INTEGER I,X\n"
"      REAL A\n"
"      COMMON /DATA/ I,X(4),A(2,3)\n"
"      PRINT*, \"I=\",I\n"
"      PRINT*, \"X=[\",X,\"]\"\n"
"      PRINT*, \"A=[\"\n"
"      PRINT*, \"[\",A(1,1),\",\",A(1,2),\",\",A(1,3),\"]\"\n"
"      PRINT*, \"[\",A(2,1),\",\",A(2,2),\",\",A(2,3),\"]\"\n"
"      PRINT*, \"]\"\n"
"      END\n"
"C END OF COMMON.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:319
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m common common.f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:323
msgid ""
">>> import common\n"
">>> print(common.data.__doc__)\n"
"i : 'i'-scalar\n"
"x : 'i'-array(4)\n"
"a : 'f'-array(2,3)\n"
"\n"
">>> common.data.i = 5\n"
">>> common.data.x[1] = 2 \n"
">>> common.data.a = [[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]\n"
">>> common.foo()\n"
">>> common.foo()\n"
" I=           5\n"
" X=[           0           2           0           0 ]\n"
" A=[\n"
" [   1.00000000     ,   2.00000000     ,   3.00000000     ]\n"
" [   4.00000000     ,   5.00000000     ,   6.00000000     ]\n"
" ]\n"
">>> common.data.a[1] = 45\n"
">>> common.foo()\n"
" I=           5\n"
" X=[           0           2           0           0 ]\n"
" A=[\n"
" [   1.00000000     ,   2.00000000     ,   3.00000000     ]\n"
" [   45.0000000     ,   45.0000000     ,   45.0000000     ]\n"
" ]\n"
">>> common.data.a                 # a is Fortran-contiguous\n"
"array([[  1.,   2.,   3.],\n"
"       [ 45.,  45.,  45.]], dtype=float32)\n"
">>> common.data.a.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:328
msgid "Fortran 90 module data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:330
msgid ""
"The F2PY interface to Fortran 90 module data is similar to the handling of "
"Fortran 77 common blocks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:333 ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:351
msgid "Consider the following Fortran 90 code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:335
msgid ""
"module mod\n"
"  integer i\n"
"  integer :: x(4)\n"
"  real, dimension(2,3) :: a\n"
"  real, allocatable, dimension(:,:) :: b \n"
"contains\n"
"  subroutine foo\n"
"    integer k\n"
"    print*, \"i=\",i\n"
"    print*, \"x=[\",x,\"]\"\n"
"    print*, \"a=[\"\n"
"    print*, \"[\",a(1,1),\",\",a(1,2),\",\",a(1,3),\"]\"\n"
"    print*, \"[\",a(2,1),\",\",a(2,2),\",\",a(2,3),\"]\"\n"
"    print*, \"]\"\n"
"    print*, \"Setting a(1,2)=a(1,2)+3\"\n"
"    a(1,2) = a(1,2)+3\n"
"  end subroutine foo\n"
"end module mod\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:338
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m moddata moddata.f90``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:342
msgid ""
">>> import moddata\n"
">>> print(moddata.mod.__doc__)\n"
"i : 'i'-scalar\n"
"x : 'i'-array(4)\n"
"a : 'f'-array(2,3)\n"
"b : 'f'-array(-1,-1), not allocated\n"
"foo()\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
">>> moddata.mod.i = 5  \n"
">>> moddata.mod.x[:2] = [1,2]\n"
">>> moddata.mod.a = [[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]\n"
">>> moddata.mod.foo()                \n"
" i=           5\n"
" x=[           1           2           0           0 ]\n"
" a=[\n"
" [   1.000000     ,   2.000000     ,   3.000000     ]\n"
" [   4.000000     ,   5.000000     ,   6.000000     ]\n"
" ]\n"
" Setting a(1,2)=a(1,2)+3\n"
">>> moddata.mod.a               # a is Fortran-contiguous\n"
"array([[ 1.,  5.,  3.],\n"
"       [ 4.,  5.,  6.]], dtype=float32)\n"
">>> moddata.mod.a.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:347
msgid "Allocatable arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:349
msgid "F2PY has basic support for Fortran 90 module allocatable arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:353
msgid ""
"module mod\n"
"  real, allocatable, dimension(:,:) :: b \n"
"contains\n"
"  subroutine foo\n"
"    integer k\n"
"    if (allocated(b)) then\n"
"       print*, \"b=[\"\n"
"       do k = 1,size(b,1)\n"
"          print*, b(k,1:size(b,2))\n"
"       enddo\n"
"       print*, \"]\"\n"
"    else\n"
"       print*, \"b is not allocated\"\n"
"    endif\n"
"  end subroutine foo\n"
"end module mod\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:356
msgid "and wrap it using ``f2py -c -m allocarr allocarr.f90``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/python-usage.rst:360
msgid ""
">>> import allocarr\n"
">>> print(allocarr.mod.__doc__)\n"
"b : 'f'-array(-1,-1), not allocated\n"
"foo()\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``foo``.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.foo()  \n"
" b is not allocated\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.b = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]             # allocate/"
"initialize b\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.foo()\n"
" b=[\n"
"   1.000000       2.000000       3.000000    \n"
"   4.000000       5.000000       6.000000    \n"
" ]\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.b                                      # b is Fortran-"
"contiguous\n"
"array([[ 1.,  2.,  3.],\n"
"       [ 4.,  5.,  6.]], dtype=float32)\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.b.flags.f_contiguous\n"
"True\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.b = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6], [7, 8, 9]]  # reallocate/"
"initialize b\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.foo()\n"
" b=[\n"
"   1.000000       2.000000       3.000000    \n"
"   4.000000       5.000000       6.000000    \n"
"   7.000000       8.000000       9.000000    \n"
" ]\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.b = None                               # deallocate array\n"
">>> allocarr.mod.foo()\n"
" b is not allocated\n"
msgstr ""
